We experienced a very low performance in DataFrame Merge procedure for big data frames with ~20K and ~70K rows with total 20M rows in the result.

The original idea that was implemented in the low performance code:

foreach (var kvp in newOccurrences)
{
    var newValue = kvp.Value.Where(i => occurrences[kvp.Key].Contains(i)).ToArray();
    if (newValue.Any())
    {
        shrinkedOccurences.Add(kvp.Key, newValue);
    }
}

The first optimization is to use hash sets and calculate intersection natively on each iteration:

foreach (var newOccurrence in newOccurrences)
{
    var newOccurrenceKey = newOccurrence.Key;

    var occurrencesHash = new HashSet<long>(occurrences[newOccurrenceKey]);
    var newOccurrencesHash = new HashSet<long>(newOccurrence.Value);

    newOccurrencesHash.IntersectWith(occurrencesHash);

    if (newOccurrencesHash.Any())
    {
        shrinkedOccurences.Add(newOccurrenceKey, newOccurrencesHash);
    }
}

But there is a high memory consumption that we can improve.

We can avoid usage of hash sets when we know that occurrences are the collections of sorted indexes. Knowledge of that gives us the following implementation of two lists intersections:

var i = 0;
var j = 0;

while (i < sortedList1.Count && j < sortedList2.Count)
{
  var item1 = sortedList1[i];

  while (j < sortedList2.Count)
  {
    var item2 = sortedList2[j];

    if (item1 < item2)
    {
      i++;
      break;
    }
    else if (item1 == item2)
    {
      crossing.Add(item1);
      i++;
      j++;
      break;
    }
    else
    {
      j++;
    }
  }
}

In the version with hash sets we consumed ~20Gb of memory in our example, but in the optimized we see that consumed up to ~500Mb of memory. And speed performance also is the best.

Also there is splitted merge procedure to more smaller functions and improved readability of code.

